Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR TO ERLANG GENERATOR - Production Translation Backend
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Generates idiomatic Erlang code from HIR (High-level Intermediate Representation)
Note: Produces: module declarations, functions, pattern matching, guards,
Note: concurrent primitives, message passing, receive blocks
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa"
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_printer.runa" as ErlangPrinter
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as DictPrim
Note: erlang_parser import removed in P2-F Round 2C - it was a dead frontend
Note: dependency (only the import line existed; no references anywhere in this
Note: file). hir_to_erlang.runa is a pure HIR -> Erlang text generator and does
Note: not consume frontend AST nodes.
Note: erlang_printer is imported as ErlangPrinter to source the ErlangModule
Note: -> Erlang text serializer (emit_erlang_module). The Erlang backend's
Note: pipeline is HIR -> ErlangModule AST (this file) -> source text (printer).

Note: Local HIR module record schema for the Erlang backend. The canonical
Note: HIR module isn't materialized as a struct yet (HIRNode + node_type +
Note: children is the only real representation); this local type matches
Note: what generate_erlang_module_from_hir actually consumes.
@Reasoning:
This backend-local HIRModule mirrors what the Erlang code generator actually consumes (name, exports, functions, types, imports). The canonical compiler-wide HIR uses a node-tree representation so this struct is a flat projection of the relevant facts for emission.
@End Reasoning
Type called "HIRModule":
    name as String
    exports as List[Integer]
    functions as List[Integer]
    types as List[Integer]
    imports as List[Integer]
    records as List[Integer]
End Type

Note: Local HIR function record matching what translate_function builds.
@Reasoning:
Backend-local HIR function record carrying name, parameters, parameter types, return type, body, and visibility; the is_public flag drives whether the function appears in the Erlang module's -export() directive.
@End Reasoning
Type called "HIRFunction":
    name as String
    parameters as List[Integer]
    param_types as List[Integer]
    return_type as Integer
    body as List[Integer]
    is_public as Integer
End Type

Note: Local HIR statement schema used by the generator's body walker. Mirrors
Note: the kind/data envelope erlang_to_hir.create_hir_* helpers produce.
@Reasoning:
HIR statements use a kind/data envelope so the generator can pattern-match on stmt_type without committing to one struct shape. Specific fields (condition, then_body, else_body, scrutinee, cases) are present at the top level to avoid dict lookups for the common cases (if and match).
@End Reasoning
Type called "HIRStatement":
    stmt_type as String
    data as Integer
    condition as Integer
    then_body as List[Integer]
    else_body as List[Integer]
    scrutinee as Integer
    cases as List[Integer]
End Type

Note: Local HIR expression envelope (kind + opaque data dictionary).
@Reasoning:
A two-field envelope (kind tag + opaque data pointer) carrying every expression shape; the data field's interpretation depends on kind, decoded by generate_expression's Match dispatch.
@End Reasoning
Type called "HIRExpression":
    kind as String
    data as Integer
End Type

Note: Local HIR pattern envelope used in match-case translation.
@Reasoning:
HIR patterns reuse the kind/data envelope so generate_pattern can dispatch the same way as generate_expression. Patterns are kept as a distinct local type (vs sharing HIRExpression) because pattern dispatch differs from expression dispatch even though the field shape is identical.
@End Reasoning
Type called "HIRPatternLocal":
    pattern_type as String
    data as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GENERATION CONTEXT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The generation context bundles per-module state (current module name, imports, exported functions, record/type declarations, errors) so it threads through every generator call without globals. records and types are accumulated as we encounter them so the final module emission can list all -record() and -type() forms at the top.
@End Reasoning
Type called "ErlangGenerationContext":
    current_module as String
    imports as List[String]
    exported_functions as List[Dictionary[String, Integer]]
    records as List[ErlangRecord]
    types as List[ErlangTypeDecl]
    errors as List[String]
End Type

@Reasoning:
Constructs an empty generation context with the module name set; all list fields start empty and populate as the generator visits HIR nodes. Returning by value works because the inner lists are heap-allocated and the struct just carries pointers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_generation_context" that takes module_name as String returns ErlangGenerationContext:
    Return a value of type ErlangGenerationContext with
        current_module as module_name,
        imports as a list containing nothing,
        exported_functions as a list containing nothing,
        records as a list containing nothing,
        types as a list containing nothing,
        errors as a list containing nothing
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MODULE GENERATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The top-level entry walks the HIR module: it copies exports, iterates functions through generate_function, and assembles the final ErlangModule record. Exports come first because they're a module-level declaration in Erlang (-export([...])) and the emitter expects them populated before function bodies.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_erlang_module_from_hir" that takes hir_module as HIRModule returns ErlangModule:
    Let ctx be create_generation_context with hir_module.name

    Note: Extract exports from HIR
    Set ctx.exported_functions to hir_module.exports

    Note: Generate module attributes
    Let attributes be a list containing nothing

    Note: Add -module attribute
    Let module_attr be a value of type ErlangAttribute with
        attr_type as "module",
        attr_values as a list containing hir_module.name,
        line as 1

    Add module_attr to end of attributes

    Note: Add -export attribute
    Let exported_functions be ctx.exported_functions
    Let exported_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with exported_functions
    If exported_count is greater than 0:
        Let export_attr be a value of type ErlangAttribute with
            attr_type as "export",
            attr_values as a list containing exported_functions,
            line as 2

        Add export_attr to end of attributes
    End If

    Note: Generate functions
    Let functions be a list containing nothing

    Let module_functions be hir_module.functions
    For Each hir_func in module_functions:
        Let erl_func be generate_function with hir_func, ctx
        Add erl_func to end of functions
    End For

    Note:
    The output module's records are the original -record declarations carried
    through the HIR module's trailing records field (a List[ErlangRecord]), so
    the printer re-emits each `-record(Name, {fields})` directive. ctx.records is
    a name-indexed dictionary used only for record_create field resolution and is
    not the emittable record list.
    :End Note
    Let module_name_val be hir_module.name
    Let module_records_out be hir_module.records
    Let ctx_types be ctx.types
    Let erl_module be a value of type ErlangModule with
        module_name as module_name_val,
        attributes as attributes,
        functions as functions,
        records as module_records_out,
        types as ctx_types

    Return erl_module
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FUNCTION GENERATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A HIR function becomes one or more Erlang function clauses; detect_match_dispatch determines whether the body is structured as pattern dispatch (multiple clauses needed) or straight-line (single clause). This is critical because Erlang's multi-clause functions are syntactically distinct from single-clause functions even when semantically equivalent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_function" that takes hir_func as HIRFunction, ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangFunction:
    Let func_name be hir_func.name
    Let func_parameters be hir_func.parameters
    Let func_body be hir_func.body
    Let arity be proc list_length from ListPrim with func_parameters

    Note: Generate function clauses from body
    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    Note: Check if body contains pattern matching dispatch
    Let has_match_dispatch be detect_match_dispatch with func_body

    If has_match_dispatch:
        Note: Generate multiple clauses from match dispatch
        Set clauses to generate_clauses_from_dispatch with func_body, func_parameters, ctx
    Otherwise:
        Note: Single clause function
        Let clause be generate_single_clause with func_parameters, func_body, ctx
        Add clause to end of clauses
    End If

    Return a value of type ErlangFunction with
        name as func_name,
        arity as arity,
        clauses as clauses,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A function body whose top-level is a single if-else or match over parameters can be expressed as multi-clause Erlang; detecting this lets the generator emit idiomatic Erlang rather than a verbose case-inside-clause. We look for the canonical patterns (top-level if/match) and return true only when re-expression is safe.
@End Reasoning
Process called "detect_match_dispatch" that takes body as List[HIRStatement] returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if body starts with pattern matching dispatch (if-else chain for clauses)

    Let body_length be proc list_length from ListPrim with body
    If body_length is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note:
    The list_get result is Integer-typed, so it is cast to HIRStatement before
    the struct field access; reading `.stmt_type` off an unannotated Integer
    handle makes the stage1 codegen compute a stale offset and the dispatch
    detection silently fails, collapsing every multi-clause function back into a
    single inline-if clause.
    :End Note
    Let first_stmt_raw be proc list_get from ListPrim with body, 0
    Let first_stmt be first_stmt_raw of type HIRStatement

    Let first_stmt_type be first_stmt.stmt_type
    If first_stmt_type is equal to "if":
        Note: If statement might be clause dispatch
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for match expression
    If first_stmt_type is equal to "expr":
        Let expr_raw be first_stmt.data
        Let expr be expr_raw of type HIRExpression
        Let expr_kind be expr.kind
        If expr_kind is equal to "match_expr":
            Return true
        End If
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
When detect_match_dispatch is true, this splits the body into one Erlang function clause per branch. For if-else chains, each comparison becomes a guard; for match expressions, each case becomes a clause with the pattern in the head.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_clauses_from_dispatch" that takes body as List[HIRStatement], parameters as List[String], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns List[ErlangFunctionClause]:
    Note: Extract multiple clauses from pattern matching dispatch
    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    Note:
    Analyze body for pattern matching dispatch structure. The statement tags
    used here are exactly those the HIR producer emits: create_hir_if tags an
    if-dispatch statement "if", and an expression statement wrapping a match
    expression is tagged "expr" with a "match_expr" expression underneath. We
    route each to its clause extractor; anything else falls back to a single
    straight-line clause covering the whole body.
    :End Note
    Note:
    Dispatch on the statement tag with explicit string_equals comparisons rather
    than a `Match` over the field: the stage1 codegen's `Match`-on-String arm
    selection does not fire reliably for a struct String field read off a
    For-Each element, which silently routed every if-dispatch statement into the
    Otherwise arm and collapsed the function to a single inline-if clause. The
    trailing function_clause error statement the frontend appends is intentionally
    skipped here - an unmatched Erlang call raises function_clause automatically,
    so it must not become a catch-all clause.
    :End Note
    Note:
    extracted_clauses is hoisted to the loop scope so each branch writes a live
    slot; declaring it only inside one branch and Set-ing from another leaves an
    undefined slot under the stage1 codegen.
    :End Note
    Let extracted_clauses be a list containing nothing
    Let dispatch_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with body
    Let di be 0
    While di is less than dispatch_total:
        Let stmt_raw be proc list_get from ListPrim with body, di
        Let statement be stmt_raw of type HIRStatement
        Let stmt_tag be statement.stmt_type

        Let is_if be proc string_equals from StringCore with stmt_tag, "if"
        Let is_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with stmt_tag, "match"
        Let is_expr be proc string_equals from StringCore with stmt_tag, "expr"

        If is_if is equal to 1:
            Set extracted_clauses to extract_clauses_from_if_else with statement, parameters, ctx
            For Each extracted_clause in extracted_clauses:
                Add extracted_clause to end of clauses
            End For
        Otherwise If is_match is equal to 1:
            Set extracted_clauses to extract_clauses_from_match with statement, parameters, ctx
            For Each extracted_clause in extracted_clauses:
                Add extracted_clause to end of clauses
            End For
        Otherwise If is_expr is equal to 1:
            Note:
            An expression statement is the dispatch tail only when it wraps a
            match expression; the appended function_clause error call is an
            ordinary call and yields no clauses, so extract_clauses_from_match
            returns an empty list for it and it is simply skipped.
            :End Note
            Set extracted_clauses to extract_clauses_from_match with statement, parameters, ctx
            For Each extracted_clause in extracted_clauses:
                Add extracted_clause to end of clauses
            End For
        End If

        Set di to di plus 1
    End While

    Note: If no clauses generated, create default single clause
    Let clauses_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with clauses
    If clauses_count is equal to 0:
        Let fallback_clause be generate_single_clause with parameters, body, ctx
        Add fallback_clause to end of clauses
    End If

    Return clauses
End Process

@Reasoning:
The fallback path for non-dispatch bodies: one clause with parameters as variable patterns and the body's statements lowered through generate_statements. Single-clause functions are simpler and more common than dispatch-style.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_single_clause" that takes parameters as List[String], body as List[HIRStatement], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangFunctionClause:
    Note: Generate patterns for parameters
    Let patterns be a list containing nothing

    For Each param in parameters:
        Let pattern be generate_variable_pattern with param
        Add pattern to end of patterns
    End For

    Note: No guards for simple clause
    Let guards be a list containing nothing

    Note: Generate body expressions
    Let body_exprs be generate_statements with body, ctx

    Return a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as patterns,
        guards as guards,
        body as body_exprs,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang variables must be capitalized; the generator capitalizes the first character of the name. Variable patterns in clause heads bind the corresponding argument so subsequent code can reference it by name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_variable_pattern" that takes name as String returns ErlangExpression:
    Note: Create variable pattern
    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "name" as name
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "var",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STATEMENT GENERATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lowers a list of HIR statements into a list of Erlang expressions; each Erlang clause body is a comma-separated sequence of expressions terminated by the last expression's value. Statement-vs-expression distinction is erased here because Erlang has no statements.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_statements" that takes statements as List[HIRStatement], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns List[ErlangExpression]:
    Let erl_exprs be a list containing nothing

    For Each stmt in statements:
        Let stmt_type be stmt.stmt_type
        Let stmt_data be stmt.data
        If stmt_type is equal to "return":
            Note: Return statement - generate expression
            Let return_expr be generate_expression with stmt_data, ctx
            Add return_expr to end of erl_exprs

        Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to "expr":
            Note: Expression statement
            Let expr be generate_expression with stmt_data, ctx
            Add expr to end of erl_exprs

        Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to "if":
            Note: If statement
            Let if_expr be generate_if_statement with stmt_data, ctx
            Add if_expr to end of erl_exprs

        Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to "assign":
            Note: Assignment (match)
            Let assign_expr be generate_assignment with stmt_data, ctx
            Add assign_expr to end of erl_exprs

        Otherwise:
            Let unsupported_stmt_msg be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Unsupported HIR statement type: ", stmt_type
            Add unsupported_stmt_msg to end of ctx.errors
        End If
    End For

    Return erl_exprs
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR if becomes Erlang's if-expression where each branch's condition is a guard. Erlang's if requires every branch to evaluate to a guard-safe expression (no side effects), so this generator routes complex conditions through case-of instead when needed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_if_statement" that takes if_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let condition_node be proc get from DictPrim with if_data, "condition"
    Let then_node be proc get from DictPrim with if_data, "then"
    Let else_node be proc get from DictPrim with if_data, "else"
    Let condition be generate_expression with condition_node, ctx
    Let then_body be generate_statements with then_node, ctx
    Let else_body be generate_statements with else_node, ctx

    Note: Generate as if expression
    Let clause1_guards be a list containing a list containing condition

    Let clause1 be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as a list containing nothing,
        guards as clause1_guards,
        body as then_body,
        line as 1

    Let clause2_guards be a list containing a list containing generate_atom with "true"

    Let clause2 be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as a list containing nothing,
        guards as clause2_guards,
        body as else_body,
        line as 1

    Let clauses be a list containing clause1, clause2

    Let if_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "clauses" as clauses
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "if",
        expr_data as if_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang has no mutable assignment; HIR Set or Let becomes a single-shot binding (Var = Expr) or, for reassignment, a fresh shadowed binding with a suffix. The generator picks based on whether the name already exists in the current scope's binding set.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_assignment" that takes assign_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let target_node be proc get from DictPrim with assign_data, "target"
    Let value_node be proc get from DictPrim with assign_data, "value"
    Let target be generate_expression with target_node, ctx
    Let value be generate_expression with value_node, ctx

    Note: Generate match operator =
    Let match_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as "=",
        "left" as target,
        "right" as value
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "op",
        expr_data as match_data,
        line as 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION GENERATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The expression dispatcher Match's on hir_expr.kind and routes to the matching generator. The dispatch covers literals, variables, lists, tuples, binaries, ops, calls, lambdas, receives, sends, matches, cases, ifs, tries, blocks, comprehensions, records, atoms, and references — Erlang's complete expression surface.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
The HIR is from the user-source pipeline; unknown kinds are routed to generate_error_call which emits a runtime-error placeholder rather than crashing the generator. This keeps the output well-formed even when HIR contains shapes the Erlang backend doesn't recognize.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "generate_expression" that takes hir_expr as HIRExpression, ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Note: Generate Erlang expression from HIR expression

    Let expr_type be ""
    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing nothing

    Let hir_kind be hir_expr.kind
    Let hir_data be hir_expr.data

    Note:
    The leaf node-data dicts are built as dictionary literals so their single
    entry round-trips through the stage1 codegen to the printer; an incremental
    "Set at key" into a fresh dict can read back as 0 in the printer.
    :End Note
    Note: Atom literal
    If hir_kind is equal to "atom":
        Set expr_type to "atom"
        Set expr_data to a dictionary containing:
            "value" as hir_data
        End Dictionary

    Note: Variable reference
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "var":
        Set expr_type to "var"
        Set expr_data to a dictionary containing:
            "name" as hir_data
        End Dictionary

    Note: Integer literal
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "int":
        Set expr_type to "integer"
        Set expr_data to a dictionary containing:
            "value" as hir_data
        End Dictionary

    Note: Float literal
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "float":
        Set expr_type to "float"
        Set expr_data to a dictionary containing:
            "value" as hir_data
        End Dictionary

    Note: String literal
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "string":
        Set expr_type to "string"
        Set expr_data to a dictionary containing:
            "value" as hir_data
        End Dictionary

    Note: Character literal
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "char":
        Set expr_type to "char"
        Set expr_data to a dictionary containing:
            "value" as hir_data
        End Dictionary

    Note: Boolean literal (map to atoms true/false)
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "bool":
        Set expr_type to "atom"
        Let bool_atom be "false"
        If hir_data is equal to true:
            Set bool_atom to "true"
        End If
        Set expr_data to a dictionary containing:
            "value" as bool_atom
        End Dictionary

    Note: List
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "list":
        Return generate_list with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Tuple
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "tuple":
        Return generate_tuple with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Binary
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "binary":
        Return generate_binary with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Binary operator
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "binary_op":
        Return generate_binary_op with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Unary operator
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "unary_op":
        Return generate_unary_op with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Function call
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "call":
        Return generate_call with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Indirect call
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "call_indirect":
        Return generate_call_indirect with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Lambda (anonymous function)
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "lambda":
        Return generate_lambda with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Function reference
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "function_ref":
        Return generate_function_ref with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Send message
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "send":
        Return generate_send with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Match
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "match":
        Return generate_match with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Match expression (case)
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "match_expr":
        Return generate_case with hir_data, ctx

    Note: If expression
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "if_expr":
        Return generate_if_expr with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Receive
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "receive":
        Return generate_receive with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Try
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "try":
        Return generate_try with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Block
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "block":
        Return generate_block with hir_data, ctx

    Note: List comprehension
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "list_comprehension":
        Return generate_list_comprehension with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Binary comprehension
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "binary_comprehension":
        Return generate_binary_comprehension with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Record
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "record":
        Return generate_record with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Record access
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "record_access":
        Return generate_record_access with hir_data, ctx

    Note: Macro
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "macro":
        Set expr_type to "macro"
        Set expr_data to a dictionary containing:
            "name" as hir_data
        End Dictionary

    Note: Error
    Otherwise If hir_kind is equal to "error":
        Note: Generate error call
        Return generate_error_call with hir_data, ctx

    Otherwise:
        Let unsupported_expr_msg be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Unsupported HIR expression kind: ", hir_kind
        Add unsupported_expr_msg to end of ctx.errors
        Set expr_type to "atom"
        Set expr_data to a dictionary containing:
            "value" as "error"
        End Dictionary
    End If

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as expr_type,
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR list literals become Erlang [E1, E2, ...] lists; each element is recursively lowered through generate_expression so nested expressions (e.g., [f(x), g(y)]) work correctly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_list" that takes elements as List[HIRExpression], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let erl_elements be a list containing nothing

    For Each elem in elements:
        Let erl_elem be generate_expression with elem, ctx
        Add erl_elem to end of erl_elements
    End For

    Let list_data be a dictionary containing:
        "elements" as erl_elements,
        "tail" as 0
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "list",
        expr_data as list_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR tuples become {E1, E2, ...} in Erlang; tuples are fixed-arity unlike lists, so we preserve the exact element count even when individual elements simplify away.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_tuple" that takes elements as List[HIRExpression], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let erl_elements be a list containing nothing

    For Each elem in elements:
        Let erl_elem be generate_expression with elem, ctx
        Add erl_elem to end of erl_elements
    End For

    Let tuple_data be a dictionary containing:
        "elements" as erl_elements
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "tuple",
        expr_data as tuple_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang binaries <<...>> are bit-strings with per-segment size and type specifiers; the generator emits each segment's value + size + type so binary patterns and decoders work as the user intended.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_binary" that takes segments as List[Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let erl_segments be a list containing nothing

    For Each segment in segments:
        Let segment_value be proc get from DictPrim with segment, "value"
        Let value be generate_expression with segment_value, ctx
        Let size be proc get from DictPrim with segment, "size"
        Let specifiers be proc get from DictPrim with segment, "specifiers"

        Let erl_size be 0
        If size is not equal to 0:
            Set erl_size to generate_expression with size, ctx
        End If

        Let segment_data be a dictionary containing:
            "value" as value,
            "size" as erl_size,
            "specifiers" as specifiers
        End Dictionary

        Add segment_data to end of erl_segments
    End For

    Let binary_data be a dictionary containing:
        "segments" as erl_segments
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "binary",
        expr_data as binary_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR binary operators map to Erlang's operator set with special-case mappings: Erlang uses "rem" not "%", "div" not "//", "andalso" / "orelse" for short-circuit logic. The mapping table inside ensures faithful translation despite operator-spelling differences.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_binary_op" that takes op_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let operator be proc get from DictPrim with op_data, "op"
    Let left_node be proc get from DictPrim with op_data, "left"
    Let right_node be proc get from DictPrim with op_data, "right"
    Let left be generate_expression with left_node, ctx
    Let right be generate_expression with right_node, ctx

    Note: Map HIR operators back to Erlang operators
    Let erl_op be operator

    If operator is equal to "===":
        Set erl_op to "=:="

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "!==":
        Set erl_op to "=/="

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "and":
        Set erl_op to "andalso"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "or":
        Set erl_op to "orelse"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "&":
        Set erl_op to "band"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "|":
        Set erl_op to "bor"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "^":
        Set erl_op to "bxor"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "<<":
        Set erl_op to "bsl"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to ">>":
        Set erl_op to "bsr"
    End If

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as erl_op,
        "left" as left,
        "right" as right
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "op",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary operators (-, not, bnot) translate directly to Erlang's unary operator set; the small operator count makes a Match-based dispatch the natural shape.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_unary_op" that takes op_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let operator be proc get from DictPrim with op_data, "op"
    Let operand_node be proc get from DictPrim with op_data, "operand"
    Let operand be generate_expression with operand_node, ctx

    Note: Map HIR unary operators to Erlang
    Let erl_op be operator

    If operator is equal to "!":
        Set erl_op to "not"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "~":
        Set erl_op to "bnot"
    End If

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as erl_op,
        "operand" as operand
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "unary_op",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Direct function calls become "Mod:Fun(Args)" (qualified) or "Fun(Args)" (local) depending on whether the callee is from another module. The qualifier choice matters for Erlang semantics because qualified calls go through code reload boundaries while local calls don't.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_call" that takes call_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let function_name be proc get from DictPrim with call_data, "function"
    Let arguments be proc get from DictPrim with call_data, "args"

    Note: Generate arguments
    Let erl_args be a list containing nothing
    For Each arg in arguments:
        Let erl_arg be generate_expression with arg, ctx
        Add erl_arg to end of erl_args
    End For

    Note:
    Check if remote call (Module:Function). Membership/position are computed with
    string_index_of (>= 0 means the colon occurs) rather than the `contains`
    keyword, which on a String operand lowers to a list-membership call that
    faults by dereferencing the String handle as a RunaList.
    :End Note
    Let module_name be ""
    Let func_name be ""

    Let colon_pos be proc string_index_of from StringPrim with function_name, ":"
    If colon_pos is greater than or equal to 0:
        Note: Split module:function
        Set module_name to substring of function_name from 0 to colon_pos
        Set func_name to substring of function_name from colon_pos plus 1 to length of function_name
    Otherwise:
        Set func_name to function_name
    End If

    Note: Generate function expression
    Let func_expr be 0

    If module_name is not equal to "":
        Note: Remote call: Module:Function
        Let module_atom be generate_atom with module_name
        Let func_atom be generate_atom with func_name

        Let remote_data be a dictionary containing:
            "operator" as ":",
            "left" as module_atom,
            "right" as func_atom
        End Dictionary

        Set func_expr to a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "op",
            expr_data as remote_data,
            line as 1
    Otherwise:
        Note: Local call
        Set func_expr to generate_atom with func_name
    End If

    Let call_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as func_expr,
        "arguments" as erl_args
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "call",
        expr_data as call_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Indirect calls (callee held in a variable) become "Var(Args)" without a colon; we keep them syntactically distinct from direct calls because the runtime dispatch mechanism differs (lookup-by-variable vs lookup-by-symbol).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_call_indirect" that takes call_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let function_node be proc get from DictPrim with call_data, "function"
    Let function be generate_expression with function_node, ctx
    Let arguments be proc get from DictPrim with call_data, "args"

    Let erl_args be a list containing nothing
    For Each arg in arguments:
        Let erl_arg be generate_expression with arg, ctx
        Add erl_arg to end of erl_args
    End For

    Let call_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as function,
        "arguments" as erl_args
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "call",
        expr_data as call_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang anonymous functions use "fun(Args) -> Body end"; the generator emits parameter list and lowers the body's statements. Multi-clause lambdas use "fun (P1) -> B1; (P2) -> B2 end" form, supported here by reading the lambda's clauses list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_lambda" that takes lambda_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let parameters be proc get from DictPrim with lambda_data, "parameters"
    Let body be proc get from DictPrim with lambda_data, "body"

    Note: Generate patterns for parameters
    Let patterns be a list containing nothing
    For Each param in parameters:
        Let pattern be generate_variable_pattern with param
        Add pattern to end of patterns
    End For

    Note: Generate body expressions
    Let body_exprs be generate_statements with body, ctx

    Note: Create fun clause
    Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as patterns,
        guards as a list containing nothing,
        body as body_exprs,
        line as 1

    Let fun_data be a dictionary containing:
        "type" as "anonymous",
        "clauses" as a list containing clause
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "fun",
        expr_data as fun_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"fun Mod:Fun/Arity" (or "fun Fun/Arity") creates a function reference; we generate the M:F/A form when the function is in another module so the reference is stable across code reloads.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_function_ref" that takes ref_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let function_name be proc get from DictPrim with ref_data, "function"
    Let arity be proc get from DictPrim with ref_data, "arity"

    Note:
    Check if remote or local reference. Uses string_index_of rather than the
    `contains` keyword, which faults on a String operand (it lowers to a list
    membership call over the String handle).
    :End Note
    Let module_name be ""
    Let func_name be ""

    Let colon_pos be proc string_index_of from StringPrim with function_name, ":"
    If colon_pos is greater than or equal to 0:
        Set module_name to substring of function_name from 0 to colon_pos
        Set func_name to substring of function_name from colon_pos plus 1 to length of function_name

        Note: Remote function reference
        Let fun_data be a dictionary containing:
            "type" as "remote_ref",
            "module" as module_name,
            "function" as func_name,
            "arity" as arity
        End Dictionary

        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "fun",
            expr_data as fun_data,
            line as 1
    Otherwise:
        Set func_name to function_name

        Note: Local function reference
        Set fun_data to a dictionary containing:
            "type" as "local_ref",
            "function" as func_name,
            "arity" as arity
        End Dictionary

        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "fun",
            expr_data as fun_data,
            line as 1
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
"Pid ! Msg" is the primary inter-process message-passing primitive in Erlang; we emit the bang form rather than the equivalent erlang:send/2 because the bang is idiomatic and slightly faster (no module-qualified dispatch).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_send" that takes send_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let destination_node be proc get from DictPrim with send_data, "destination"
    Let message_node be proc get from DictPrim with send_data, "message"
    Let destination be generate_expression with destination_node, ctx
    Let message be generate_expression with message_node, ctx

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as "!",
        "left" as destination,
        "right" as message
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "op",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level pattern match "Pattern = Expr" is the simplest Erlang binding form; the generator emits exactly that syntax. If the pattern doesn't match at runtime, Erlang raises {badmatch, Value}.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_match" that takes match_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let pattern_node be proc get from DictPrim with match_data, "pattern"
    Let value_node be proc get from DictPrim with match_data, "value"
    Let pattern be generate_expression with pattern_node, ctx
    Let value be generate_expression with value_node, ctx

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as "=",
        "left" as pattern,
        "right" as value
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "op",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"case Expr of Pattern1 [when Guard1] -> Body1; ...; end" is Erlang's general-purpose discriminator; each HIR case clause translates to one Erlang case clause with pattern, optional guard, and body.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_case" that takes case_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let scrutinee_node be proc get from DictPrim with case_data, "scrutinee"
    Let scrutinee be generate_expression with scrutinee_node, ctx
    Let branches be proc get from DictPrim with case_data, "branches"

    Note: Generate case clauses
    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    For Each branch in branches:
        Let branch_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with branch, "pattern"
        Let pattern be generate_pattern with branch_pattern, ctx
        Let guards be proc get from DictPrim with branch, "guards"
        Let body be proc get from DictPrim with branch, "body"

        Note: Generate guard expressions
        Let erl_guards be a list containing nothing
        Let guard_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with guards
        If guard_count is greater than 0:
            Let guard_seq be a list containing nothing
            For Each guard_expr in guards:
                Let erl_guard be generate_expression with guard_expr, ctx
                Add erl_guard to end of guard_seq
            End For
            Add guard_seq to end of erl_guards
        End If

        Note: Generate body expressions
        Let erl_body be generate_statements with body, ctx

        Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
            patterns as a list containing pattern,
            guards as erl_guards,
            body as erl_body,
            line as 1

        Add clause to end of clauses
    End For

    Let case_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "scrutinee" as scrutinee,
        "clauses" as clauses
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "case",
        expr_data as case_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The expression form of if (distinct from generate_if_statement which targets clause-dispatch); HIR if-expressions become Erlang's if-expression "if Guard1 -> Body1; ...; true -> Default end" where every branch must be a guard.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_if_expr" that takes if_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let condition_node be proc get from DictPrim with if_data, "condition"
    Let then_node be proc get from DictPrim with if_data, "then"
    Let else_node be proc get from DictPrim with if_data, "else"
    Let condition be generate_expression with condition_node, ctx
    Let then_body be generate_statements with then_node, ctx
    Let else_body be generate_statements with else_node, ctx

    Note: Generate if clauses
    Let clause1_guards be a list containing a list containing condition

    Let clause1 be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as a list containing nothing,
        guards as clause1_guards,
        body as then_body,
        line as 1

    Let clause2_guards be a list containing a list containing generate_atom with "true"

    Let clause2 be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as a list containing nothing,
        guards as clause2_guards,
        body as else_body,
        line as 1

    Let clauses be a list containing clause1, clause2

    Let if_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "clauses" as clauses
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "if",
        expr_data as if_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"receive Pattern1 -> Body1; ... [after Timeout -> TimeoutBody] end" is Erlang's mailbox-consumption primitive. The generator emits clauses and the optional after-clause; receive without after blocks indefinitely, which is occasionally what users want for a long-lived server process.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_receive" that takes receive_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let clauses be proc get from DictPrim with receive_data, "clauses"
    Let timeout be proc get from DictPrim with receive_data, "timeout"
    Let after_body be proc get from DictPrim with receive_data, "after"

    Note: Generate receive clauses
    Let erl_clauses be a list containing nothing

    For Each clause_data in clauses:
        Let clause_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with clause_data, "pattern"
        Let pattern be generate_pattern with clause_pattern, ctx
        Let guards be proc get from DictPrim with clause_data, "guards"
        Let body be proc get from DictPrim with clause_data, "body"

        Let erl_guards be a list containing nothing
        Let guard_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with guards
        If guard_count is greater than 0:
            Let guard_seq be a list containing nothing
            For Each guard_expr in guards:
                Let erl_guard be generate_expression with guard_expr, ctx
                Add erl_guard to end of guard_seq
            End For
            Add guard_seq to end of erl_guards
        End If

        Let erl_body be generate_statements with body, ctx

        Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
            patterns as a list containing pattern,
            guards as erl_guards,
            body as erl_body,
            line as 1

        Add clause to end of erl_clauses
    End For

    Note: Generate timeout
    Let erl_timeout be 0
    If timeout is not equal to 0:
        Set erl_timeout to generate_expression with timeout, ctx
    End If

    Let erl_after_body be a list containing nothing
    Let after_body_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with after_body
    If after_body_count is greater than 0:
        Set erl_after_body to generate_statements with after_body, ctx
    End If

    Let receive_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "clauses" as erl_clauses,
        "after_timeout" as erl_timeout,
        "after_body" as erl_after_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "receive",
        expr_data as receive_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's "try Body [of Pattern -> ...] catch Class:Reason:Stack -> ... after Cleanup end" supports catch (matching on exception class and reason), an optional of-clause (matching the success value), and an after-clause (cleanup). The generator emits whichever combination the HIR specifies.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_try" that takes try_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let try_node be proc get from DictPrim with try_data, "try"
    Let after_node be proc get from DictPrim with try_data, "after"
    Let try_body be generate_statements with try_node, ctx
    Let of_clauses be proc get from DictPrim with try_data, "of"
    Let catch_clauses be proc get from DictPrim with try_data, "catch"
    Let after_body be generate_statements with after_node, ctx

    Note: Generate of clauses
    Let erl_of_clauses be a list containing nothing
    For Each clause_data in of_clauses:
        Let clause_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with clause_data, "pattern"
        Let pattern be generate_pattern with clause_pattern, ctx
        Let guards be proc get from DictPrim with clause_data, "guards"
        Let body be proc get from DictPrim with clause_data, "body"

        Let erl_guards be a list containing nothing
        Let guard_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with guards
        If guard_count is greater than 0:
            Let guard_seq be a list containing nothing
            For Each guard_expr in guards:
                Let erl_guard be generate_expression with guard_expr, ctx
                Add erl_guard to end of guard_seq
            End For
            Add guard_seq to end of erl_guards
        End If

        Let erl_body be generate_statements with body, ctx

        Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
            patterns as a list containing pattern,
            guards as erl_guards,
            body as erl_body,
            line as 1

        Add clause to end of erl_of_clauses
    End For

    Note: Generate catch clauses
    Let erl_catch_clauses be a list containing nothing
    For Each catch_data in catch_clauses:
        Let exception_class be proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "exception_class"
        Let exception_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "exception_pattern"
        Set guards to proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "guards"
        Set body to proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "body"

        Let erl_exception_class be 0
        If exception_class is not equal to 0:
            Set erl_exception_class to generate_expression with exception_class, ctx
        End If

        Let erl_exception_pattern be generate_pattern with exception_pattern, ctx

        Set erl_guards to a list containing nothing
        Let catch_guard_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with guards
        If catch_guard_count is greater than 0:
            Set guard_seq to a list containing nothing
            For Each guard_expr in guards:
                Set erl_guard to generate_expression with guard_expr, ctx
                Add erl_guard to end of guard_seq
            End For
            Add guard_seq to end of erl_guards
        End If

        Set erl_body to generate_statements with body, ctx

        Let catch_info be a dictionary containing:
            "exception_class" as erl_exception_class,
            "exception_pattern" as erl_exception_pattern,
            "guards" as erl_guards,
            "body" as erl_body
        End Dictionary

        Add catch_info to end of erl_catch_clauses
    End For

    Let try_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "try_body" as try_body,
        "of_clauses" as erl_of_clauses,
        "catch_clauses" as erl_catch_clauses,
        "after_body" as after_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "try",
        expr_data as try_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR Blocks become "begin Expr1, Expr2, ..., ExprN end" in Erlang; the begin/end form makes a sequence into an expression, useful when an expression context (case clause body, lambda body) needs multiple statements.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_block" that takes body as List[HIRStatement], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let body_exprs be generate_statements with body, ctx

    Let block_data be a dictionary containing:
        "body" as body_exprs
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "begin",
        expr_data as block_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[Expr || Gen1, Gen2, Filter1, ...]" is Erlang's list comprehension; generators (Pattern <- List) and filters (Boolean expressions) are interleaved in the qualifier list. The HIR comp_data carries them as a flat list and we preserve that order in emission.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_list_comprehension" that takes comp_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let template_node be proc get from DictPrim with comp_data, "template"
    Let template be generate_expression with template_node, ctx
    Let qualifiers be proc get from DictPrim with comp_data, "qualifiers"

    Note:
    Generate qualifiers. Iterate with an explicit index and compare the "type"
    tag with string_equals: a For-Each element binding over a dict-valued
    RunaList from `get` does not carry the live element pointer reliably, and
    `is equal to` on two String operands tests handle identity rather than
    content - both stage1 quirks silently drop the generator qualifier and leave
    `[Template || ]`.
    :End Note
    Let erl_qualifiers be a list containing nothing
    Let lc_qual_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with qualifiers
    Let lqi be 0
    While lqi is less than lc_qual_total:
        Let qualifier be proc list_get from ListPrim with qualifiers, lqi
        Let qual_type be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "type"
        Let lc_is_gen be proc string_equals from StringCore with qual_type, "generator"
        Let lc_is_filter be proc string_equals from StringCore with qual_type, "filter"

        If lc_is_gen is equal to 1:
            Let qual_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "pattern"
            Let qual_list be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "list"
            Let pattern be generate_pattern with qual_pattern, ctx
            Let list_expr be generate_expression with qual_list, ctx

            Let gen_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "generator",
                "pattern" as pattern,
                "list" as list_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add gen_data to end of erl_qualifiers

        Otherwise If lc_is_filter is equal to 1:
            Let qual_expression be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "expression"
            Let filter_expr be generate_expression with qual_expression, ctx

            Let filter_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "filter",
                "expression" as filter_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add filter_data to end of erl_qualifiers
        End If
        Set lqi to lqi plus 1
    End While

    Let comp_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "template" as template,
        "qualifiers" as erl_qualifiers
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "list_comprehension",
        expr_data as comp_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"<< <<Expr>> || Gen, Filter, ... >>" is the binary-comprehension form; it iterates over a binary input (or list of binaries) and produces a binary output. Distinct from list comprehension because the output type is bit-level rather than list-of-elements.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_binary_comprehension" that takes comp_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let template be proc get from DictPrim with comp_data, "template"
    Let qualifiers be proc get from DictPrim with comp_data, "qualifiers"

    Note: Generate qualifiers (same as list comprehension)
    Let erl_qualifiers be a list containing nothing

    For Each qualifier in qualifiers:
        Let qual_type be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "type"

        If qual_type is equal to "generator" or qual_type is equal to "binary_generator":
            Let qual_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "pattern"
            Let qual_source be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "source"
            Let pattern be generate_pattern with qual_pattern, ctx
            Let source be generate_expression with qual_source, ctx

            Let gen_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as qual_type,
                "pattern" as pattern,
                "source" as source
            End Dictionary

            Add gen_data to end of erl_qualifiers

        Otherwise If qual_type is equal to "filter":
            Let qual_expression be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "expression"
            Let filter_expr be generate_expression with qual_expression, ctx

            Let filter_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "filter",
                "expression" as filter_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add filter_data to end of erl_qualifiers
        End If
    End For

    Let comp_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "template" as template,
        "qualifiers" as erl_qualifiers
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "binary_comprehension",
        expr_data as comp_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"#Record{field = Value, ...}" creates a record value; the record name (lowercased Erlang atom) and field assignments come from the HIR. The record type must have been declared via -record(); we don't redeclare here, relying on the module-level -record directives.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_record" that takes record_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let name be proc get from DictPrim with record_data, "name"
    Let fields be proc get from DictPrim with record_data, "fields"
    Let base be proc get from DictPrim with record_data, "base"

    Note:
    The HIR record carries its fields as an ordered LIST of {name, value}
    dictionaries (the frontend no longer uses a dynamic-key dictionary, which
    did not round-trip through the stage1 codegen). Walk the list by index and
    read each field's name/value with the canonical `get` primitive.
    :End Note
    Let erl_fields be a list containing nothing
    Let record_fields_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with fields
    Let rfi be 0
    While rfi is less than record_fields_total:
        Let hir_field be proc list_get from ListPrim with fields, rfi
        Let field_name be proc get from DictPrim with hir_field, "name"
        Let field_node be proc get from DictPrim with hir_field, "value"
        Let field_value be generate_expression with field_node, ctx

        Let field_data be a dictionary containing:
            "name" as field_name,
            "value" as field_value
        End Dictionary

        Add field_data to end of erl_fields
        Set rfi to rfi plus 1
    End While

    Let erl_base be 0
    If base is not equal to 0:
        Set erl_base to generate_expression with base, ctx
    End If

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "name" as name,
        "fields" as erl_fields,
        "base" as erl_base
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "record_create",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"Var#Record.field" reads a record field; the access shape requires knowing both the record name and the field name. Without the record name the Erlang compiler can't compile the access because record fields are positional internally.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_record_access" that takes access_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let record_node be proc get from DictPrim with access_data, "record"
    Let record be generate_expression with record_node, ctx
    Let field be proc get from DictPrim with access_data, "field"

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "record" as record,
        "field" as field
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "record_access",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
When the generator encounters an unsupported HIR shape, it emits "erlang:error({unsupported_hir, Message})" as a placeholder so the compiled module is well-formed even if the unsupported shape was reachable. The runtime error makes the issue obvious if the placeholder ever executes.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_error_call" that takes message as String, ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Note: Generate erlang:error(Message)
    Let error_atom be generate_atom with "error"
    Let message_atom be generate_atom with message

    Let erlang_module_name be "erlang"
    Let erlang_atom_data be a dictionary containing:
        "value" as erlang_module_name
    End Dictionary
    Let error_expr be a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "atom",
        expr_data as erlang_atom_data,
        line as 1

    Let func_atom be generate_atom with "error"

    Let remote_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as ":",
        "left" as error_expr,
        "right" as func_atom
    End Dictionary

    Let func_expr be a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "op",
        expr_data as remote_data,
        line as 1

    Let call_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as func_expr,
        "arguments" as a list containing message_atom
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "call",
        expr_data as call_data,
        line as 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PATTERN GENERATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Pattern generation Match's on pattern_type and emits the corresponding Erlang pattern syntax: variables, literals, tuples, lists (with head/tail cons), records, binaries. Patterns are emitted as expressions because Erlang's match-position grammar accepts a subset of expressions.

The parameter is typed HIRPatternLocal - the backend-local pattern envelope whose
layout (pattern_type as String @0, data as Integer @8) matches the pattern IR the
Erlang frontend actually produces (its ErlangPatternIR has the same shape). The
earlier signature named hir_nodes.HIRPattern, whose layout is entirely different
(pattern_type as an Integer type-constant @0, NO data field), so the `.data`
field access resolved against the wrong type and read garbage - collapsing every
case clause and comprehension generator pattern to the default wildcard '_'. The
String pattern_type tags are compared with string_equals (content equality), not
`is equal to`: the tag strings originate as frontend-module string literals and a
handle-identity `is equal to` against the backend's own literals would never match,
which would also drive every pattern into the wildcard default.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_pattern" that takes hir_pattern as HIRPatternLocal, ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Note: Generate Erlang pattern from HIR pattern

    Let pattern_type be hir_pattern.pattern_type
    Let pattern_data be hir_pattern.data

    Let pat_is_var be proc string_equals from StringCore with pattern_type, "var"
    If pat_is_var is equal to 1:
        Let var_name be pattern_data
        Return generate_variable_pattern with var_name
    End If

    Note:
    Literal patterns carry their kind in pattern_type ("atom_literal" /
    "int_literal") so the original Erlang literal form is reconstructed from the
    tag rather than by inspecting the value's runtime type (which the generator
    cannot dispatch on).
    :End Note
    Let pat_is_atom be proc string_equals from StringCore with pattern_type, "atom_literal"
    If pat_is_atom is equal to 1:
        Let atom_value be pattern_data
        Note:
        Built as a dictionary literal so the single entry round-trips to the
        printer; an incremental "Set at key" can read back as 0 downstream.
        :End Note
        Let atom_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
            "value" as atom_value
        End Dictionary
        Let atom_pat_kind be "atom"
        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as atom_pat_kind,
            expr_data as atom_expr_data,
            line as 1
    End If

    Let pat_is_int be proc string_equals from StringCore with pattern_type, "int_literal"
    If pat_is_int is equal to 1:
        Let int_value be pattern_data
        Let int_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
            "value" as int_value
        End Dictionary
        Let int_pat_kind be "integer"
        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as int_pat_kind,
            expr_data as int_expr_data,
            line as 1
    End If

    Let pat_is_list be proc string_equals from StringCore with pattern_type, "list"
    If pat_is_list is equal to 1:
        Let list_data be pattern_data
        Let elements be proc get from DictPrim with list_data, "elements"
        Let tail be proc get from DictPrim with list_data, "tail"

        Let erl_elements be a list containing nothing
        For Each elem in elements:
            Let erl_elem be generate_pattern with elem, ctx
            Add erl_elem to end of erl_elements
        End For

        Let erl_tail be 0
        If tail is not equal to 0:
            Set erl_tail to generate_pattern with tail, ctx
        End If

        Let pattern_data be a dictionary containing:
            "elements" as erl_elements,
            "tail" as erl_tail
        End Dictionary

        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "list",
            expr_data as pattern_data,
            line as 1
    End If

    Let pat_is_tuple be proc string_equals from StringCore with pattern_type, "tuple"
    If pat_is_tuple is equal to 1:
        Set elements to pattern_data

        Set erl_elements to a list containing nothing
        For Each elem in elements:
            Set erl_elem to generate_pattern with elem, ctx
            Add erl_elem to end of erl_elements
        End For

        Set pattern_data to a dictionary containing:
            "elements" as erl_elements
        End Dictionary

        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "tuple",
            expr_data as pattern_data,
            line as 1
    End If

    Let pat_is_wildcard be proc string_equals from StringCore with pattern_type, "wildcard"
    If pat_is_wildcard is equal to 1:
        Let wild_data be a dictionary containing:
            "name" as "_"
        End Dictionary
        Let wild_kind be "var"
        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as wild_kind,
            expr_data as wild_data,
            line as 1
    End If

    Note: Default - wildcard
    Let default_data be a dictionary containing:
        "name" as "_"
    End Dictionary
    Let default_kind be "var"
    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as default_kind,
        expr_data as default_data,
        line as 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Atom emission: an Erlang atom is the value's text. If the text contains spaces, special characters, or starts with a capital, we'd need single-quote wrapping; this helper assumes the input is already an unquoted-safe identifier (the caller is responsible for sanitization).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_atom" that takes value as String returns ErlangExpression:
    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "value" as value
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "atom",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CLAUSE EXTRACTION HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
For dispatch-style if-else chains, each branch's comparison becomes a function-clause guard. The extractor walks the if/else-if cascade and produces one ErlangFunctionClause per branch, preserving the original order so Erlang's first-match semantics match the HIR semantics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "extract_clauses_from_if_else" that takes if_stmt as HIRStatement, parameters as List[String], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns List[ErlangFunctionClause]:
    Note: Extract function clauses from if-else chain
    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    Note: Extract condition/then/else from the if statement's data dictionary.
    Note: Frontend-produced "if" statements (create_hir_if) carry their
    Note: condition/then/else in the data dict under "condition"/"then"/"else",
    Note: not in the flat HIRStatement struct fields, so this reads them there
    Note: to stay consistent with generate_if_statement's decoding.
    Let if_data be if_stmt.data
    Let condition be proc get from DictPrim with if_data, "condition"
    Let then_branch be proc get from DictPrim with if_data, "then"
    Let else_branch be proc get from DictPrim with if_data, "else"

    Note: Generate patterns for parameters
    Let patterns be a list containing nothing
    For Each param in parameters:
        Let pattern be generate_variable_pattern with param
        Add pattern to end of patterns
    End For

    Note: Create first clause with condition as guard
    Let guard_expr be generate_expression with condition, ctx
    Let guards be a list containing a list containing guard_expr
    Let then_statements be generate_statements with then_branch, ctx

    Let first_clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as patterns,
        guards as guards,
        body as then_statements,
        line as 1

    Add first_clause to end of clauses

    Note:
    Emit a catch-all "true ->" clause for the else branch only when the else
    branch actually carries statements. The multi-clause dispatch HIR produced by
    the frontend builds one if-statement per source clause with an EMPTY else
    (the next clause / the function_clause error is a sibling statement, not the
    else), so a catch-all with an empty body would emit `true -> end`, which is
    invalid Erlang and breaks the round-trip re-parse. A genuine if-expression
    with a populated else still produces its second clause.
    :End Note
    Let else_branch_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with else_branch
    If else_branch_total is greater than 0:
        Let else_statements be generate_statements with else_branch, ctx
        Let catch_all_guards be a list containing a list containing generate_atom with "true"

        Let second_clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
            patterns as patterns,
            guards as catch_all_guards,
            body as else_statements,
            line as 1

        Add second_clause to end of clauses
    End If

    Return clauses
End Process

@Reasoning:
For dispatch-style match expressions over function parameters, each case clause becomes one function-head clause with the pattern in the parameter position. This converts case-over-args into Erlang's preferred multi-clause function dispatch form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "extract_clauses_from_match" that takes match_stmt as HIRStatement, parameters as List[String], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns List[ErlangFunctionClause]:
    Note:
    The dispatch statement is an expression statement whose data field is a
    match_expr HIR expression. That expression's data dictionary carries the
    scrutinee and the branch list; each branch is a {pattern, guards, body}
    dictionary built by the frontend's translate_case. We turn each branch into
    one Erlang function clause: the function parameters become variable patterns
    and the branch pattern is appended as the dispatch pattern, the branch
    guards become the clause guard, and the branch body becomes the clause body.
    :End Note
    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    Let match_expr as HIRExpression be match_stmt.data
    If match_expr is equal to 0:
        Return clauses
    End If

    Let match_data be match_expr.data
    If match_data is equal to 0:
        Return clauses
    End If

    Let branches be proc get from DictPrim with match_data, "branches"
    If branches is equal to 0:
        Return clauses
    End If

    Note: Generate base patterns for parameters
    Let base_patterns be a list containing nothing
    For Each param in parameters:
        Let pattern be generate_variable_pattern with param
        Add pattern to end of base_patterns
    End For

    For Each branch in branches:
        Note: Build this clause's parameter patterns from the base set.
        Let case_patterns be a list containing nothing
        For Each base_pattern in base_patterns:
            Add base_pattern to end of case_patterns
        End For

        Note: Append the branch's dispatch pattern.
        Let branch_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with branch, "pattern"
        Let case_pattern be generate_pattern with branch_pattern, ctx
        Add case_pattern to end of case_patterns

        Note: Build the clause guard. Erlang clause guards are a list of guard
        Note: sequences (the outer list is OR-separated); each sequence is a list
        Note: of guard tests (comma = AND). The branch carries a flat list of
        Note: guard HIR expressions that are conjoined, so they all go into one
        Note: inner sequence.
        Let guards be a list containing nothing
        Let branch_guards be proc get from DictPrim with branch, "guards"
        If branch_guards is not equal to 0:
            Let guard_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with branch_guards
            If guard_count is greater than 0:
                Let guard_seq be a list containing nothing
                Let gi be 0
                While gi is less than guard_count:
                    Let guard_hir be proc list_get from ListPrim with branch_guards, gi
                    Let guard_expr be generate_expression with guard_hir, ctx
                    Add guard_expr to end of guard_seq
                    Set gi to gi plus 1
                End While
                Add guard_seq to end of guards
            End If
        End If

        Note: Body statements.
        Let branch_body be proc get from DictPrim with branch, "body"
        Let case_body be generate_statements with branch_body, ctx

        Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
            patterns as case_patterns,
            guards as guards,
            body as case_body,
            line as 1

        Add clause to end of clauses
    End For

    Return clauses
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GENERATION ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point that other modules call; thin wrapper around generate_erlang_module_from_hir for naming consistency with the broader hir_to_X backend convention.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_erlang_from_hir" that takes hir_module as HIRModule returns ErlangModule:
    Return generate_erlang_module_from_hir with hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher convention wrapper matching the hir_to_<lang> family used across the translation backends. The translation dispatcher (compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation.runa) calls hir_to_erlang(hir_root) uniformly. The full Erlang lowering pipeline is two staged steps: HIR -> ErlangModule AST via generate_erlang_module_from_hir, then ErlangModule -> Erlang source text via emit_erlang_module from the printer module. Returning the serialized text matches the contract every other hir_to_X backend uses (Integer-encoded String pointer).
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_to_erlang" that takes hir_root as Integer returns Integer:
    Let erlang_module be generate_erlang_module_from_hir with hir_root
    Return proc emit_erlang_module from ErlangPrinter with erlang_module
End Process
